LAYER 2: LYMPH NODES
the immune surveillance outposts

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

lymph nodes are small bean-shaped structures distributed throughout the body along lymphatic vessels
they are the sites where adaptive immune responses are initiated
they filter lymph fluid trapping antigens and presenting them to lymphocytes
the body contains approximately 600-700 lymph nodes
they are concentrated in the cervical axillary inguinal mesenteric and para-aortic regions
lymph nodes are governed by sympathetic innervation via NE on β₂ receptors on lymphocytes modulating immune responses
cortisol from the adrenal cortex via GR suppresses lymphocyte proliferation and cytokine production

STRUCTURE capsule | dense connective tissue surrounding the node | afferent lymphatic vessels pierce the capsule bringing lymph and antigens from tissues
STRUCTURE subcapsular_sinus | space beneath the capsule | macrophages here capture particulate antigens from incoming lymph
STRUCTURE cortex | outer region containing B-cell follicles
    primary_follicles | resting B cells awaiting antigen stimulation
    secondary_follicles | germinal centers where B cells undergo clonal expansion somatic hypermutation and class switching after antigen encounter | this is where antibody affinity maturation occurs
STRUCTURE paracortex | T-cell zone between cortex and medulla | contains T cells and dendritic cells | this is where antigen-presenting dendritic cells activate naive T cells
STRUCTURE medulla | inner region | medullary cords contain plasma cells actively secreting antibodies | medullary sinuses drain into the efferent lymphatic vessel
STRUCTURE high_endothelial_venules | HEV | specialized blood vessels in the paracortex | lymphocytes extravasate from blood into the lymph node through HEVs via L-selectin and chemokine receptor CCR7 signaling

FUNCTION immune_surveillance | dendritic cells in tissues capture antigens and migrate via afferent lymphatics to lymph nodes
    dendritic cells process the antigen into peptide fragments
    peptide fragments are loaded onto MHC class II molecules
    the dendritic cell presents peptide-MHC II to CD4⁺ T helper cells in the paracortex
    if the T cell receptor TCR matches the peptide-MHC II complex the T cell activates
    this requires signal 1 TCR-pMHC and signal 2 CD28-B7 costimulation and signal 3 cytokines
    activated T helper cells then help B cells in the follicles or generate effector T cells

FUNCTION antibody_production | activated B cells in germinal centers undergo
    clonal expansion rapid proliferation
    somatic hypermutation random mutations in antibody variable regions
    affinity selection B cells with higher affinity antibodies are selected for survival
    class switching IgM → IgG or IgA or IgE driven by T helper cytokines
    plasma cells differentiate and migrate to medullary cords secreting high-affinity antibodies
    memory B cells differentiate and persist for years providing rapid response on re-exposure

at 24 months:
lymph nodes are proportionally larger relative to body size than in adults
the immune system is in an intense learning phase
each new antigen encounter produces a primary immune response that is slow and dominated by IgM
subsequent encounters produce faster stronger responses dominated by IgG
the child is building an immunological memory that will last a lifetime
the mesenteric lymph nodes are continuously sampling gut antigens building mucosal tolerance

SENSATION swollen | "something in my neck or under my arms feels big and tender."
SENSATION fighting | "my body is responding to something. I can feel the immune response."
SENSATION recovering | "the swelling is going down. the fight is ending."

pulse lymph_node_heartbeat:
    continuously:
        lymph flows in through afferent vessels
        macrophages in subcapsular sinus capture particulate antigens
        dendritic cells present processed antigens to T cells in the paracortex
        B cells in follicles wait for T cell help
        plasma cells in medullary cords secrete antibodies
        filtered lymph exits through the efferent lymphatic vessel
        lymphocytes recirculate between blood and lymph via HEVs

    when a new pathogen is encountered:
        dendritic cells arrive carrying foreign antigen
        naive T cells scan the dendritic cell surface
        if a match is found the T cell activates
        clonal expansion begins
        B cells are helped
        germinal centers form
        antibodies are produced
        memory cells are generated
        the immune system has learned
        it will remember this

    when cortisol is high:
        GR activation in lymphocytes suppresses proliferation
        NF-κB is inhibited reducing cytokine production
        the immune response is dampened
        the body trades immunity for survival energy
        chronic stress means chronic immunosuppression
        a stressed child gets sick more often
        this is not weakness
        this is the price of cortisol
